        <span class="big">Pandoc</span>
        &nbsp;
        <span class="small">a universal document converter</span>
    </div>
    <div id="bd">
      <div id="yui-main">
        <div class="yui-b">
          <h1 class="title">About pandoc</h1>
<p
>If you need to convert files from one markup format into another, pandoc is your swiss-army knife. Need to generate a man page from a markdown file? No problem. LaTeX to Docbook? Sure. HTML to MediaWiki? Yes, that too. Pandoc can read <a href="http://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/"
  >markdown</a
  > and (subsets of) <a href="http://docutils.sourceforge.net/docs/ref/rst/introduction.html"
  >reStructuredText</a
  >, <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/html40/"
  >HTML</a
  >, and <a href="http://www.latex-project.org/"
  >LaTeX</a
  >, and it can write plain text, <a href="http://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/"
  >markdown</a
  >, <a href="http://docutils.sourceforge.net/docs/ref/rst/introduction.html"
  >reStructuredText</a
  >, <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/html40/"
  >HTML</a
  >, <a href="http://www.latex-project.org/"
  >LaTeX</a
  >, <a href="http://www.pragma-ade.nl/"
  >ConTeXt</a
  >, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portable_Document_Format"
  >PDF</a
  >, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_Text_Format"
  >RTF</a
  >, <a href="http://www.docbook.org/"
  >DocBook XML</a
  >, <a href="http://opendocument.xml.org/"
  >OpenDocument XML</a
  >, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenDocument"
  >ODT</a
  >, <a href="http://www.gnu.org/software/texinfo/"
  >GNU Texinfo</a
  >, <a href="http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Help:Formatting"
  >MediaWiki markup</a
  >, <a href="http://developer.apple.com/DOCUMENTATION/Darwin/Reference/ManPa"
  >groff man</a
  > pages, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EPUB"
  >EPUB</a
  > ebooks, and <a href="http://meyerweb.com/eric/tools/s5/"
  >S5</a
  > and <a href="http://www.w3.org/Talks/Tools/Slidy"
  >Slidy</a
  > HTML slide shows. PDF output (via LaTeX) is also supported with the included <code
  >markdown2pdf</code
  > wrapper script.</p
><p
>Pandoc understands a number of useful <a href="http://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/"
  >markdown</a
  > syntax extensions, including document metadata (title, author, date); footnotes; tables; definition lists; superscript and subscript; strikeout; enhanced ordered lists (start number and numbering style are significant); delimited code blocks; markdown inside HTML blocks; and TeX math. Other options include “smart” quotes, dashes, and ellipses; syntax highlighting; and automatically generated tables of contents. If strict markdown compatibility is desired, all of these extensions can be turned off with a command-line flag.</p
><p
>Pandoc includes a Haskell library and a standalone executable. The library includes separate modules for each input and output format. So adding a new input or output format just requires adding a new module.</p
><p
>Pandoc is free software, released under the <a href="http://www.gnu.org/copyleft/gpl.html"
  >GPL</a
  >. © 2006–2010 <a href="http://johnmacfarlane.net/"
  >John MacFarlane</a
  >.</p
>
